copies of "The
Cantos."

49:46.851 --> 49:51.956 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But Hemingway, on the other
hand, takes what's
viable from their styles and
adds it to his

49:51.989 --> 49:56.827 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
own instinct -- instinctive
style. And he
knows that he has commercially
successful

49:56.861 --> 49:59.697 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
work, and he's going to showcase
that in "The
Sun Also Rises."

49:59.730 --> 50:02.700 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: And that made his
reputation,
or certainly helped it, his
reputation.

50:02.733 --> 50:04.668 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
LESLEY M.M. BLUME: It brokered
his reputation.

50:04.702 --> 50:09.406 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Yes. Yes. How
exactly? Was
it the style? The character of
the man? What

50:09.440 --> 50:10.875 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
was it, do you think?

50:10.908 --> 50:12.643 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
LESLEY M.M. BLUME: It was a
combination of
a lot of different things.

50:12.676 --> 50:17.982 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Hemingway himself and
Hemingway's writing
were both brilliant, brilliant
cocktails.

50:18.015 --> 50:22.720 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so with Hemingway's writing,
he famously
wrote to one of his publishers
-- he said,

50:22.753 --> 50:27.892 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
you don't need a high school
education to
enjoy my writing. And it's going
to titillate

50:27.925 --> 50:32.062 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the masses. I mean, anybody can
relate to
it, but the style is so
revolutionary that

50:32.096 --> 50:35.499 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
it will titillate highbrow
critics, which
it did.

50:35.532 --> 50:40.838 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And then he said, for people who
are not interested
in the stylistic components of
it, there's

50:40.871 --> 50:45.843 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
a lot of -- quote -- "dope about
high society,"
and that is always interesting.
So, there

50:45.876 --> 50:50.214 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
was something for everyone. That
was one of
the things that helped him bring
that revolutionary

50:50.247 --> 50:53.951 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
style to the masses in a way
that somebody
like Gertrude Stein and Ezra
Pound is just

50:53.984 --> 50:55.719 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
not going to be able to do.

50:55.753 --> 50:59.990 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Those always went
hand in hand
with Hemingway, right, the
writing and the

51:00.024 --> 51:01.725 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
biography.

51:01.759 --> 51:06.430 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
How did -- when you think about
the ideas,
the views of Hemingway, they
have bounced

51:06.463 --> 51:11.001 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
around over the decades, right,
of how people
have seen him. How did you come
to see him?

51:11.035 --> 51:12.069 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Did you like him?

51:12.102 --> 51:13.837 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
LESLEY M.M. BLUME: It's an
interesting question.

51:13.871 --> 51:19.543 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I spent an awful lot of time
with Hemingway.
And Hemingway had a remarkable
ability to

51:19.576 --> 51:23.213 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
reach very noble goals through
sometimes ignoble
means.

51:23.247 --> 51:28.452 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I think the question is less
a question
of whether or not I like him or
whether you

51:28.485 --> 51:35.192 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
forgive what he did in the
service of his
ambition. And Hemingway's talent
was so outsized,

51:35.225 --> 51:40.230 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that I feel like I can forgive
him a lot of
his trespasses to have achieved
what he did

51:40.264 --> 51:40.864 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
achieve.

51:40.898 --> 51:42.633 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: All right.

51:42.666 --> 51:45.569 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The book is "Everybody Behaves
Badly: The
True Story Behind Hemingway's
Masterpiece

51:45.602 --> 51:47.137 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
The Sun Also Rises."

51:47.171 --> 51:48.005 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Lesley Blume, thank you.

51:48.038 --> 51:49.406 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
LESLEY M.M. BLUME: Thank you so
much.

51:49.440 --> 51:53.644 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
