realized
that I would actually have to
tell her.

52:31.281 --> 52:36.954 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
With its naked legs and
cheesecake on the
cover, its breezy tone and
wisecracking, single-in-the-city

52:36.987 --> 52:42.860 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
heroine, I knew that my debut
wasn't a candidate
for the National Book Award. I
knew it was

52:42.893 --> 52:47.197 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
an entertaining, diverting read,
the kind
of book that would get packed in
beach bags

52:47.231 --> 52:49.700 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
or purchased for plane trips.

52:49.733 --> 52:55.005 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
What I didn't know was the way
the world would
treat books like mine, the scorn
and opprobrium

52:55.039 --> 52:59.610 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that would be heaped on what the
world would
come to call chick lit, or how
much it would

52:59.643 --> 53:02.813 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
hurt, or how completely I would
believe it.

53:02.846 --> 53:07.317 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
At some point in my life,
between birth and
publication, I had gotten the
message that

53:07.351 --> 53:12.456 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
there were books that mattered
and books that
didn't. For years, I believed
that my work

53:12.489 --> 53:17.628 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
fell squarely into the second
category. I
bought what the critics were
selling, that

53:17.661 --> 53:22.566 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
chick lit wasn't real
literature, that it
was only entertainment, that it
was even dangerous,

53:22.599 --> 53:27.504 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
a kind of fast-growing weed
pushing other
worthier books off the shelves.

53:27.538 --> 53:33.343 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But as the years went on, I
started to think,
what's wrong with something
that's -- quote

53:33.377 --> 53:38.348 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
-- "just entertaining"? Is the
problem that
I'm writing something that's
diverting and

53:38.382 --> 53:43.387 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
disposable, or that what I'm
writing is diverting,
and disposable and for women?

53:43.420 --> 53:48.959 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Is chick lit any worse than
mysteries or thrillers,
the genre fiction that men read,
the stuff

53:48.992 --> 53:54.665 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that's at least slightly more
respectable
than romance and women's
fiction? And, most

53:54.698 --> 53:57.768 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
importantly, is pleasure such a
terrible thing?

53:57.801 --> 54:03.574 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's taken time, but what I have
come to realize
is that providing enjoyment,
helping a plane

54:03.607 --> 54:09.046 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ride pass more quickly, making a
hospital
stay less excruciating, letting
a young woman

54:09.079 --> 54:15.319 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
struggling with her own
insecurities and dysfunction
feel less lonely, is a prize,
too, and it's

54:15.352 --> 54:17.321 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
one to be treasured.

54:17.354 --> 54:21.792 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so, America, as we prepare
to celebrate
our nation's freedom and head to
the beach,

54:21.825 --> 54:28.265 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
it's time to embrace the F-word:
fun. Let's
declare our independence from
the shackles

54:28.298 --> 54:34.538 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of shame. Take whatever you want
to the beach,
or the bus, or to bed. Read
without apology,

54:34.571 --> 54:36.340 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
for enrichment and enjoyment.

54:36.373 --> 54:42.713 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Whether it's spiky, challenging
postmodern
fiction, or commercial women's
fiction, or

54:42.746 --> 54:48.819 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
commercial men's fiction, more
commonly known
as books, read what you like
wherever you

54:48.852 --> 54:53.857 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
can and embrace the joy of the
stories that
make you happy.

